What Makes High Quality White Wine?

by Xinkun Chu

Introduction

This analysis use the white wine datasets, which include objective tests (e.g. PH values) and sensory data (grade by wine experts), to study the features of high graded white wine.

The dataset is from: P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

The dataset has 4898 observations with 13 variables. Among the 13 variables, 1 id. number, 11 physicochemical (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol) and 1 sensory (quality, score between 0 and 10).

The main feature is the wine quality graded by the experts between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). The task of this analysis to study which fearures affect the white wine quality. The quality table and distribution:

## 
##    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
##   20  163 1457 2198  880  175    5

The variance of the quality distribution:

## [1] 0.7843557

The distribution is slightly left skewed with 6 as the mode. The mean is 5.88, and the variance is 0.78. Few are graded lower than 4 or greater than 8.

In this analysis, all the 11 physicochemical features may correlate with the quality. Before the correlation study, check the distribution of these features first.

For the 11 features, most of them have outliers, as seen from the boxplot. These outliers will be excluded in the histogram distribution. However, the cases with grade lower than 4 or greater than 8 is also rare. It’s possible these outlies contibute to very low or very high grade. These outliers will be checked in bivariate analysis. The outliers of some feature will be retained if they converge at the two ends of quality, deleted otherwise.

Most of the features have a left skewed distribution. For the citric acid, besides the peak around 0.3, there are unusual single value peaks at 0.49 and 0.74 (g/dm3). The residual sugar distribution is highly skewed with peak around 1~2 g/L, which is expected for the kind of dry wine. We can see the distribution better by using transforming the x axis as log10.

Bivariate Plots Section

Check the correlation between these variables.

The residual sugar has a strong correlation of 0.84 with density, and the density has a strong negative correlation of -0.78 with alcohol. It seems as more sugar transformed into alcohol, the alcohol level increases. Meanwhile, more sugar transformed means less residual sugar, which leads to a lower density of the wine.

For the feature quality, it has a moderate positive correlation of 0.44 with alcohol, week negative correlation of -0.31 with density, -0.21 with chlorides, -0.19 with volatile acidity, -0.17 with total sulfur dioxide. The relationship between these features and quality will be checked.

There is a tendency that higher quality wine has higher level of alcohol.

High quality wine tends to have lower density. This agrees with result from previous plot, because density has a strong negative correlation of -0.78 with alcohol.

Higher quality wine tends to have a lower level of chlorides, and less spread in distribution.

No clear trend is seen between volatile acidity and quality from this plot.

No clear trend is seen between total sulfur dioxide and quality from this plot.

Multivariate Plots Section

From the plot, high quality white wine tends to have higher alcohol and lower density. However, alcohol and density are strongly negative correlated, which explains for the result.

From the plot, high quality white wine tends to have higher alcohol and lower chlorides.

From the plot, high quality white wine tends to have higher alcohol and lower volatile acidity.

From the plot, higher quality wine tends to have a lower level of total sulfur dioxide and higher alcohol.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The distribution is slightly left skewed. Most of the white wines are graded with 5 or 6. Few are graded lower than 4 or greater than 8. Among the 4898 observations, only 5 observation for grade 9 and 20 observation for grade 3. Because the quality is determined by the median of grade by at least 3 wine experts, it’s likely that different experts have different opinion on judging the quality of the win. So it makes sense that extremely high or low values are rare.

Plot Two

Description Two

Alcohol has a moderate positive correlation of 0.44 with quality, which is the largest correlation with quality found among the features. The boxplot shows the alcohol percentage distribution for each quality. There is a tendency that higher quality wine has higher level of alcohol. Of course, more alcohol doesn’t necessarily mean higher quality wine. Many factors may explain this tendency. It’s possible that higher alcohol are the result of better quality grapes and better fermentation.

Plot Three

Description Three

In the scatter plot of total sulfur dioxide and alcoholm, the quality are differentiate by color. Most of the light circles(wine with quality 5) converge at the right bottom of the plot. Low quality wine tends to have a higher level of total sulfur dioxide and lower alcohol. While most of the dark circles (quality 7,8) have higher level of alcohol and total sulfur dioxide less than 150 mg/dm3.

Reflection

In this analysis, the correlation between white wine quality and 11 physicochemical features are studied using a dataset of 4898 observations. It’s found that alcohol has a moderate positive correlation with quality, while density, chloride, volative acidity and total sulfur dioxide have low negative correlation with wine quality. However, it’s hard to tell what physicochemical features a good white wine should have. There is no obvious liner relationship between these factors, further study may need the tools of machine learning to train a model to dig out the complicated relationships. Also, the samples for high(>8) and low quality(<4) wine would be important for study, but the statistics is not enough in the dataset.
